    <div class="worksheet">
        <h1>Sentence Types Identification Worksheet</h1>
     

        <div class="reference-box">
            <h3>üìö Quick Reference Guide</h3>
            
            <div class="sentence-type">Simple Sentence</div>
            <div class="definition">Contains ONE independent clause (one subject and one verb).</div>
            <div class="example">Example: The dog barked loudly.</div>
            
            <div class="sentence-type">Compound Sentence</div>
            <div class="definition">Contains TWO or more independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so) or a semicolon.</div>
            <div class="example">Example: The dog barked loudly, and the cat ran away.</div>
            
            <div class="sentence-type">Complex Sentence</div>
            <div class="definition">Contains ONE independent clause and at least ONE dependent clause. Common subordinating conjunctions include: because, although, when, if, since, while, after, before, unless.</div>
            <div class="example">Example: When the dog barked loudly, the cat ran away.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="directions">
            <strong>Directions:</strong> Read each sentence carefully. Check the box that identifies the sentence type: Simple, Compound, or Complex.
        </div>

